{"title_page": "Doctor Fate (Kent V. Nelson)", "text_new": "{{additional citations|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox comics character \n| image=\n| caption=\n| character_name=Doctor Fate\n| real_name=Kent V. Nelson\n| publisher=[[DC Comics]]\n| debut= ''[[Countdown to Mystery]]'' #1 (Nov. 2007)\n| creators= [[Steve Gerber]]<br>[[Justiniano]]o\n| alliances= Justice Society of America\n| aliases= Doctor Fate\n| powers=Mastery of [[Magic in fiction|magic]]<!--Powers should be listed in the \"Powers and abilities\" section below-->\n}}\n'''Doctor Fate (Kent V. Nelson)''' is a [[fictional character|fictional]] [[superhero]] from [[DC Comics]] appearing in [[American comic book]]s published by [[DC Comics]]. He is one of the superheroes known as [[Doctor Fate]] and the grandson of [[Doctor Fate (Kent Nelson)|The original Doctor Fate]]. He's is created by [[Steve Gerber]] and [[Justiniano]].\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Publication history==\n<!--as per exemplar, real world history of the characters' use-->\nIn early 2007, DC published a bi-weekly run of one-shots depicting the search for a new Doctor Fate. These were intended to be followed by a new ''Doctor Fate'' ongoing series in April 2007, written by [[Steve Gerber]] and illustrated by [[Paul Gulacy]], featuring the new Doctor Fate.<ref>{{cite web|last=McLauchlin|first=Jim|title=A Twist of Fate|website=Wizard|date=2006-12-03|url=http://www.wizarduniverse.com/magazine/wizard/002578766.cfm|accessdate=2007-02-11|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212102237/http://www.wizarduniverse.com/magazine/wizard/002578766.cfm|archivedate=2007-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stevegerber.com/sgblog/?p=283 |title=Some Thoughts on Doctor Fate \u2013 Part 1 |website=stevegerberblog |date=2007-03-03 |accessdate=2011-01-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716174624/http://www.stevegerber.com/sgblog/?p=283 |archivedate=2011-07-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, the series was delayed due to extended production and creative difficulties. Steve Gerber said in an interview for [[Newsarama]] that the story intended for the first arc of the ''Doctor Fate'' ongoing series had been reworked to serve as the main story for ''Countdown to Mystery'', a dual-feature eight-issue miniseries with Eclipso as the second feature.<ref>{{cite web|title=DC Announcement|website=stevegerblog|date=2007-06-15|url=http://www.stevegerber.com/sgblog/2007/06/15/dc-announcement/|accessdate=2007-08-07|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200602/http://www.stevegerber.com/sgblog/2007/06/15/dc-announcement/|archivedate=2007-09-27}}</ref> The first issue of ''Countdown to Mystery'', with art by [[Justiniano]] and Walden Wong rather than Gulacy, was released in November 2007. Due to Steve Gerber's death, the seventh issue was written by [[Adam Beechen]] using Gerber's notes. The final issue was written by Beechen, [[Gail Simone]], [[Mark Waid]], and [[Mark Evanier]], who each wrote a different ending to the story.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=13096|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225150908/http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=13096|url-status=dead|archivedate=2008-02-25|title=CBR News: WonderCon: DC Nation Panel|website=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=2008-02-22|accessdate=2011-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional character biography==\nWhen the JSA looks for Hector, they find the helmet, amulet, and cloak. [[Sandy Hawkins|Sand]] dons the helmet to speak with Nabu.<ref>''JSA'' #78 (Dec. 2005)</ref> At the same moment, Mordru appears and removes the helmet from Sand, allowing Nabu to manifest through the helmet without needing a host body.<ref>''JSA'' #79 (Jan. 2006)</ref> Nabu defeats Mordru and the JSA offers him membership, which Nabu declines.<ref>''JSA'' #80 (Feb. 2006)</ref> Sensing his impending demise, Nabu gives the helmet to [[Detective Chimp]] to pass on to a new wearer, telling him it would still have certain abilities without Nabu's spirit inside. Nabu is then killed by the Spectre.<ref name=\"dayofvengeance\">{{Comic book reference|writer=[[Bill Willingham|Willingham, Bill]]|penciller=[[Justiniano]]|inker=|story=The Ninth Age of Magic|title=[[Day of Vengeance]] [[Infinite Crisis]] Special|volume=1|issue=#1|date=March, 2006|publisher=[[DC Comics]]|page=|panel=}}</ref>\n\nWhen Detective Chimp finds the helmet will not fit him, he asks [[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)|Captain Marvel]] to throw the helmet into space, allowing the helmet to find its new owner. As it travels across the universe, the helmet warps itself to resemble Kent Nelson's half helmet from the 1940s and falls back to Earth.<ref name=\"dayofvengeance\"/>\n\nThe helmet later crosses paths again with Detective Chimp,<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Detective Chimp'' #1 (Jan. 2007)</ref> [[Ibis the Invincible]],<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Ibis the Invincible'' #1 (Jan. 2007)</ref> [[Sargon the Sorcerer]],<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Sargon the Sorcerer'' #1 (Feb. 2007)</ref> [[Black Alice (comics)|Black Alice]],<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Black Alice'' #1 (Feb. 2007)</ref> and [[Zauriel]]<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Zauriel'' #1 (March 2007)</ref> before it reaches Doctor Kent V. Nelson, Kent Nelson's grandnephew, who becomes the new Doctor Fate after finding the helmet in a dumpster.<ref name=\"mystery\">''Countdown to Mystery'' #1\u20138 (Nov. 2007 \u2013 July 2008)</ref> When Nelson first wears the helmet, it reverts to its original form and clothes him in a new version of Doctor Fate's original costume.<ref name=\"mystery\"/>\n\nAfter fighting off the demon Nergal, Kent uses the helmet's magic for gambling. He later meets Maddy, an occult bookstore owner, and Inza Fox, a comic book writer, who is later killed after turning into water. When Kent turns to alcohol to cope with Inza's death, he gives the helmet to Maddy. The two are captured by Nergal, but escape when Kent overcomes his depression, restoring Inza to life in the process.<ref name=\"mystery\"/>\n\nKent helps a group of magic-using heroes escape from [[Hell (DC Comics)|Hell]]<ref>''Reign in Hell'' #8 (April 2009)</ref> and joins the Justice Society.<ref>''Justice Society of America'' (vol. 3) #30 (Oct. 2009)</ref> Kent remains with the team after it splits into two groups.  He is briefly possessed by [[Mordru]] before leaving Earth to hone his spellcasting abilities.<ref>''Justice Society of America'' (vol. 3) #35 (March 2010)</ref> Kent later returns to help the team with various problems.<ref>''Justice Society of America'' (vol. 3) #44 (Dec. 2010)</ref><ref>''Justice Society of America'' (vol. 3) #47\u201354 (March \u2013 October 2011)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia  |\n    | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and link back to that category using the {{dmoz}} template.         |\n    ======================= {{No more links}} =============================-->\n*{{comicbookdb|type=character|id=15268|title=Doctor Fate (Kent V. Nelson)}}\n*{{comicbookdb|type=storyarc|id=1905|title=''The Helmet of Fate''}}\n{{Doctor Fate|state=expanded}}\n{{Earth-Two}}\n{{Justice Society of America}}\n\n[[Category:Characters created by J. M. DeMatteis]]\n[[Category:Characters created by Steve Gerber]]\n[[Category:Comics characters introduced in 2007]]\n[[Category:DC Comics characters who use magic]]\n[[Category:DC Comics superheroes]]\n[[Category:DC Comics fantasy characters]]\n[[Category:DC Comics titles]]\n[[Category:Earth-Two]]\n[[Category:Egyptian superheroes]]\n[[Category:Fictional archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Fictional avatars]]\n[[Category:Fictional characters from parallel universes]]\n[[Category:Fictional occult and psychic detectives]]\n[[Category:Male characters in comics]]\n[[Category:Mythology in DC Comics]]\n", "text_old": "{{additional citations|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox comics character \n| image=\n| caption=\n| character_name=Doctor Fate\n| real_name=Kent V. Nelson\n| publisher=[[DC Comics]]\n| debut= ''[[Countdown to Mystery]]'' #1 (Nov. 2007)\n| creators= [[Steve Gerber]]<br>[[Justiniano]]o\n| alliances= Justice Society of America\n| aliases= Doctor Fate\n| powers=Mastery of [[Magic in fiction|magic]]<!--Powers should be listed in the \"Powers and abilities\" section below-->\n}}\n'''Doctor Fate (Kent V. Nelson)''' is a [[fictional character|fictional]] [[superhero]] from [[DC Comics]] appearing in [[American comic book]]s published by [[DC Comics]]. He is one of the superheroes known as [[Doctor Fate]] and the grandson of [[Doctor Fate (Kent Nelson)|The original Doctor Fate]]. He's is created by [[Steve Gerber]] and [[Justiniano]].\n\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Publication history==\n<!--as per exemplar, real world history of the characters' use-->\nIn early 2007, DC published a bi-weekly run of one-shots depicting the search for a new Doctor Fate. These were intended to be followed by a new ''Doctor Fate'' ongoing series in April 2007, written by [[Steve Gerber]] and illustrated by [[Paul Gulacy]], featuring the new Doctor Fate.<ref>{{cite web|last=McLauchlin|first=Jim|title=A Twist of Fate|website=Wizard|date=2006-12-03|url=http://www.wizarduniverse.com/magazine/wizard/002578766.cfm|accessdate=2007-02-11|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212102237/http://www.wizarduniverse.com/magazine/wizard/002578766.cfm|archivedate=2007-12-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stevegerber.com/sgblog/?p=283 |title=Some Thoughts on Doctor Fate \u2013 Part 1 |website=stevegerberblog |date=2007-03-03 |accessdate=2011-01-16 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716174624/http://www.stevegerber.com/sgblog/?p=283 |archivedate=2011-07-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, the series was delayed due to extended production and creative difficulties. Steve Gerber said in an interview for [[Newsarama]] that the story intended for the first arc of the ''Doctor Fate'' ongoing series had been reworked to serve as the main story for ''Countdown to Mystery'', a dual-feature eight-issue miniseries with Eclipso as the second feature.<ref>{{cite web|title=DC Announcement|website=stevegerblog|date=2007-06-15|url=http://www.stevegerber.com/sgblog/2007/06/15/dc-announcement/|accessdate=2007-08-07|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927200602/http://www.stevegerber.com/sgblog/2007/06/15/dc-announcement/|archivedate=2007-09-27}}</ref> The first issue of ''Countdown to Mystery'', with art by [[Justiniano]] and Walden Wong rather than Gulacy, was released in November 2007. Due to Steve Gerber's death, the seventh issue was written by [[Adam Beechen]] using Gerber's notes. The final issue was written by Beechen, [[Gail Simone]], [[Mark Waid]], and [[Mark Evanier]], who each wrote a different ending to the story.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=13096|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080225150908/http://www.comicbookresources.com/news/newsitem.cgi?id=13096|url-status=dead|archivedate=2008-02-25|title=CBR News: WonderCon: DC Nation Panel|website=[[Comic Book Resources]]|date=2008-02-22|accessdate=2011-01-16}}</ref>\n\n==Fictional character biography==\nWhen the JSA looks for Hector, they find the helmet, amulet, and cloak. [[Sandy Hawkins|Sand]] dons the helmet to speak with Nabu.<ref>''JSA'' #78 (Dec. 2005)</ref> At the same moment, Mordru appears and removes the helmet from Sand, allowing Nabu to manifest through the helmet without needing a host body.<ref>''JSA'' #79 (Jan. 2006)</ref> Nabu defeats Mordru and the JSA offers him membership, which Nabu declines.<ref>''JSA'' #80 (Feb. 2006)</ref> Sensing his impending demise, Nabu gives the helmet to [[Detective Chimp]] to pass on to a new wearer, telling him it would still have certain abilities without Nabu's spirit inside. Nabu is then killed by the Spectre.<ref name=\"dayofvengeance\">{{Comic book reference|writer=[[Bill Willingham|Willingham, Bill]]|penciller=[[Justiniano]]|inker=|story=The Ninth Age of Magic|title=[[Day of Vengeance]] [[Infinite Crisis]] Special|volume=1|issue=#1|date=March, 2006|publisher=[[DC Comics]]|page=|panel=}}</ref>\n\nWhen Detective Chimp finds the helmet will not fit him, he asks [[Captain Marvel (DC Comics)|Captain Marvel]] to throw the helmet into space, allowing the helmet to find its new owner. As it travels across the universe, the helmet warps itself to resemble Kent Nelson's half helmet from the 1940s and falls back to Earth.<ref name=\"dayofvengeance\"/>\n\nThe helmet later crosses paths again with Detective Chimp,<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Detective Chimp'' #1 (Jan. 2007)</ref> [[Ibis the Invincible]],<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Ibis the Invincible'' #1 (Jan. 2007)</ref> [[Sargon the Sorcerer]],<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Sargon the Sorcerer'' #1 (Feb. 2007)</ref> [[Black Alice (comics)|Black Alice]],<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Black Alice'' #1 (Feb. 2007)</ref> and [[Zauriel]]<ref>''The Helmet of Fate: Zauriel'' #1 (March 2007)</ref> before it reaches Doctor Kent V. Nelson, Kent Nelson's grandnephew, who becomes the new Doctor Fate after finding the helmet in a dumpster.<ref name=\"mystery\">''Countdown to Mystery'' #1\u20138 (Nov. 2007 \u2013 July 2008)</ref> When Nelson first wears the helmet, it reverts to its original form and clothes him in a new version of Doctor Fate's original costume.<ref name=\"mystery\"/>\n\nAfter fighting off the demon Nergal, Kent uses the helmet's magic for gambling. He later meets Maddy, an occult bookstore owner, and Inza Fox, a comic book writer, who is later killed after turning into water. When Kent turns to alcohol to cope with Inza's death, he gives the helmet to Maddy. The two are captured by Nergal, but escape when Kent overcomes his depression, restoring Inza to life in the process.<ref name=\"mystery\"/>\n\nKent helps a group of magic-using heroes escape from [[Hell (DC Comics)|Hell]]<ref>''Reign in Hell'' #8 (April 2009)</ref> and joins the Justice Society.<ref>''Justice Society of America'' (vol. 3) #30 (Oct. 2009)</ref> Kent remains with the team after it splits into two groups.  He is briefly possessed by [[Mordru]] before leaving Earth to hone his spellcasting abilities.<ref>''Justice Society of America'' (vol. 3) #35 (March 2010)</ref> Kent later returns to help the team with various problems.<ref>''Justice Society of America'' (vol. 3) #44 (Dec. 2010)</ref><ref>''Justice Society of America'' (vol. 3) #47\u201354 (March \u2013 October 2011)</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n    | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia  |\n    | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n    |                                                                     |\n    |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n    | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] for details.  |\n    |                                                                     |\n    | If there are already plentiful links, please propose additions or   |\n    | replacements on this article's discussion page, or submit your link |\n    | to the relevant category at the Open Directory Project (dmoz.org)   |\n    | and