shop International Airport (FNT)]] ([[Flint, Michigan|Flint]]) - Commercial airport located in [[Genesee County, Michigan|Genesee County]].\n*[[Coleman A. Young International Airport|Coleman A. Young International Airport (DET)]] (Detroit) - General aviation only. This airport is in Wayne County in the city of [[Detroit]].\n\n===Major highways===\n*{{jct|state=MI|I|75|name1=[[Walter Chrysler|Walter P. Chrysler]] Freeway}} is the main north-south highway in the region, serving Flint, Pontiac, Troy, and Detroit, before continuing south (as the Fisher and Detroit-Toledo Freeways) to serve many of the communities along the shore of [[Lake Erie]].\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|96}} runs northwest-southeast through Oakland County and (as the Jeffries Freeway) has its eastern terminus in downtown Detroit.\n*{{jct|state=MI|I|275}} runs north-south from I-75 in the south to the junction of I-96 and I-696 in the north, providing a bypass through the western suburbs of Detroit.\n*{{jct|country=USA|I|696|name1=[[Walter Reuther|Walter P. Reuther]] Freeway}} runs east-west from the junction of I-96 and I-275, providing a route through the northern suburbs of Detroit.  Taken together, I-275 and I-696 form a semicircle around Detroit.\n*{{jct|state=MI|US|24}} ends just outside of Clarkston at I-75. To the south, US 24 serves suburban Detroit and [[Monroe, Michigan|Monroe]] before entering [[Ohio]]. Much of US 24 in Oakland County is named Telegraph Road, and it is a major north-south road extending from [[Toledo, Ohio]], through Monroe, Wayne, and Oakland Counties to [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]]. It gained notoriety in a song (''Telegraph Road'') by the group [[Dire Straits]].\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|1|name1=Woodward Avenue}} has a northern terminus in Pontiac. The route continues southerly from Oakland County into the City of Detroit, ending downtown. The Detroit Zoo is located along M-1 in Oakland County.  M-1 is also home to the [[Woodward Dream Cruise]], a classic-car cruise from Pontiac to [[Ferndale, Michigan|Ferndale]] that is held in August. It is the largest single-day classic-car cruise in America.\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|5}}\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|10|name1=[[John C. Lodge]] Freeway}} runs largely parallel to I-75 from Southfield to downtown Detroit.  The service drives are named Northwestern Highway.\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|15}} (Ortonville Road, Main Street in Clarkston)\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|24|name1=Lapeer Road}} has a southern terminus at I-75 northeast of Pontiac. To the north, the route continues to [[Lapeer, Michigan|Lapeer]] and beyond. Note: M-24 and US 24 do not intersect at present, although this was the case until the 1950s.\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|39|name1=Southfield Freeway}} runs north-south from I-94 in Allen Park to Southfield.  North of Nine Mile Road, the freeway ends and continues as Southfield Road into Birmingham.\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|59}} (Highland Road [from Pontiac westerly], Huron Street [within Pontiac] and Veterans Memorial Freeway [Pontiac to [[Utica, Michigan|Utica]]]), continues east in Macomb County as Hall Road to [[Clinton Charter Township, Michigan|Clinton Township]] and west to I-96 near [[Howell, Michigan|Howell]]\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|102}} Perhaps better known as 8 Mile Road, M-102 follows the Oakland\u2013Wayne county line for most of its length. 8 Mile Road, known by many due to the film ''[[8 Mile (film)|8 Mile]]'', forms the dividing line between Detroit on the south and the suburbs of Macomb and Oakland counties on the north. It is also known as Baseline Road outside of Detroit, because it coincides with the [[Baseline (surveying)|baseline]] used in surveying Michigan; that baseline is also the boundary for a number of Michigan counties. It is designated M-102 for much of its length in Wayne County.\n*{{jct|state=MI|M|150|name1=Rochester Road}} serves as a spur highway from M-59 into the city of Rochester.\n*[[Grand River Avenue]] connects the suburbs of Brighton, Novi, and Farmington to downtown Detroit. The avenue follows the route of old [[U.S. Route 16 in Michigan|US&nbsp;16]] before I-96 replaced it in 1962. It is one of the five roads planned by Judge August Woodward to radiate out from Detroit and connect the city to other parts of the state.\n\n===Rail===\n[[Amtrak]]'s [[Wolverine (train)|Wolverine]] serves Oakland County with 3 daily trains each way, stopping in [[Pontiac Transportation Center|Pontiac]], [[Troy Transit Center|Troy]], [[Royal Oak station (Michigan)|Royal Oak]], and continuing on to [[Chicago Union Station|Chicago]].\n\n===Mile roads===\n{{Main|Mile Road System (Detroit)}}\n*Surface-street navigation in metro Detroit is commonly anchored by \"mile roads,\" major east-west surface streets that are spaced at one-mile (1.6&nbsp;km) intervals and increment as one travels north and away from the city center. Mile roads sometimes have two names, the numeric name (e.g., 15 Mile Road), used in Macomb County, and a local name (e.g., Maple Road), used in Oakland County (for the most part).\n\n===Bicycling===\nThe conditions on most non-residential roads in Oakland County are not favorable to bicycling. Exceptions to this are primarily in the inner-ring suburbs within the southeast corner of the county. This is due to their [[Grid plan|street grid]].\n\nA primary reason for these unfavorable cycling conditions is the [[Road Commission for Oakland County]] has a policy of not accommodating bicycles on the road. As a result, some communities have designated [[sidepath]]s (locally called \"safety paths\") as bike routes which do not meet the [[American Association of State Highway and Transportation Officials]] (AASHTO) guidelines for bicycling facilities and have been found to be less safe than on-road bike facilities.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.massbike.org/resources/stats.htm#sidewalk |title=Risk of Sidewalk and Wrong-way Riding |accessdate=March 17, 2007 |work=Bicyclist Injuries: Learning from the Statistics |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070520071232/http://www.massbike.org/resources/stats.htm#sidewalk <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = May 20, 2007}}</ref>\n\nAs a result, there are no designated [[League of American Bicyclists#Bicycle Friendly Communities|Bicycle Friendly Communities]] within Oakland County.\n\nOnly the city of [[Ferndale, Michigan|Ferndale]] has a built comprehensive bicycle network of [[bike lanes]] and signed shared roadways.\n\n==Education==\nThe County of Oakland counterpart in public education (K-12) is the [[Oakland Schools]], an [[Intermediate school district]].\n\n===Higher education===\nOakland County is home to several institutions of higher education.\n*[[Baker College]],  [[Auburn Hills, Michigan|Auburn Hills]] campus\n*[[Oakland University]], [[Rochester, Michigan|Rochester]]\n*The [[Western Michigan University Thomas M. Cooley Law School]], [[Auburn Hills, Michigan|Auburn Hills]] campus\n*[[Lawrence Technological University]], [[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]]\n*[[Rochester College]], [[Rochester, Michigan|Rochester]]\n*[[South University]], [[Novi, Michigan|Novi]] campus\n*[[Walsh College|Walsh College of Accountancy and Business]], [[Troy, Michigan|Troy]] and [[Novi, Michigan|Novi]] campuses\n*[[Oakland Community College]], five campuses: Orchard Ridge, Auburn Hills, Southfield, Highland Lakes, and Royal Oak.\n* [[Saint Mary's College (Michigan)|Saint Mary's College]] of [[Madonna University]], [[Orchard Lake, Michigan|Orchard Lake]]\n* Cranbrook College of Art, Bloomfield Hills\n\n==Sports==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | Club\n! scope=\"col\" | League\n! scope=\"col\" | Venue\n! scope=\"col\" | Established\n! scope=\"col\" | Championships\n|-\n!scope=\"row\" style=\"font-weight: normal;\" | [[Oakland County FC]]\n| [[Premier League of America]], Soccer\n| [[Clawson Park Stadium]]\n| 2015\n|\n|}\nThe NFL's [[Detroit Lions]]  played their home games at the  [[Pontiac Silverdome]]  from 1975 through 2001, when they moved to [[Ford Field]] in Downtown Detroit.  The Silverdome was also the site of [[Super Bowl XVI]], where the [[San Francisco 49ers]] defeated the [[Cincinnati Bengals]], the first of 5 Super Bowl titles for the 49ers.\n\nFrom 1988 to 2017, prior to the move to [[Little Caesars Arena]] in Detroit, the [[Detroit Pistons]] played their home games at [[The Palace of Auburn Hills]] and from 1978 to 1988, they played at the Pontiac Silverdome.\n\nThe Pontiac Silverdome has also hosted various other sporting events since it opened.\n\n==Communities==\n[[File:Oakland County, MI census map2.png|thumb|right|500px|[[United States Census|U.S. Census]] data map showing local municipal boundaries within Oakland County.  Shaded areas represent incorporated cities.]]\n\n===Cities===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Auburn Hills, Michigan|Auburn Hills]]\n*[[Berkley, Michigan|Berkley]]\n*[[Birmingham, Michigan|Birmingham]]\n*[[Bloomfield Hills, Michigan|Bloomfield Hills]]\n*[[Clarkston, Michigan|Clarkston]]\n*[[Clawson, Michigan|Clawson]]\n*[[Farmington, Michigan|Farmington]]\n*[[Farmington Hills, Michigan|Farmington Hills]]\n*[[Fenton, Michigan|Fenton]] (mostly in [[Genesee County, Michigan|Genesee County]])\n*[[Ferndale, Michigan|Ferndale]]\n*[[Hazel Park, Michigan|Hazel Park]]\n*[[Huntington Woods, Michigan|Huntington Woods]]\n*[[Keego Harbor, Michigan|Keego Harbor]]\n*[[Lake Angelus, Michigan|Lake Angelus]]\n*[[Lathrup Village, Michigan|Lathrup Village]]\n*[[Madison Heights, Michigan|Madison Heights]]\n*[[Northville, Michigan|Northville]] (partially in [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]])\n*[[Novi, Michigan|Novi]]\n*[[Oak Park, Michigan|Oak Park]]\n*[[Orchard Lake Village, Michigan|Orchard Lake Village]]\n*[[Pleasant Ridge, Michigan|Pleasant Ridge]]\n*[[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]] (county seat)\n*[[Rochester, Michigan|Rochester]]\n*[[Rochester Hills, Michigan|Rochester Hills]]\n*[[Royal Oak, Michigan|Royal Oak]]\n*[[South Lyon, Michigan|South Lyon]]\n*[[Southfield, Michigan|Southfield]]\n*[[Sylvan Lake, Michigan|Sylvan Lake]]\n*[[Troy, Michigan|Troy]]\n*[[Walled Lake, Michigan|Walled Lake]]\n*[[Wixom, Michigan|Wixom]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Villages===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Beverly Hills, Michigan|Beverly Hills]]\n*[[Bingham Farms, Michigan|Bingham Farms]]\n*[[Franklin, Michigan|Franklin]]\n*[[Holly, Michigan|Holly]]\n*[[Lake Orion, Michigan|Lake Orion]]\n*[[Leonard, Michigan|Leonard]]\n*[[Milford, Michigan|Milford]]\n*[[Ortonville, Michigan|Ortonville]]\n*[[Oxford, Michigan|Oxford]]\n*[[Wolverine Lake, Michigan|Wolverine Lake]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Charter townships===\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[Bloomfield Township, Oakland County, Michigan|Bloomfield Charter Township]]\n*[[Brandon Township, Michigan|Brandon Charter Township]]\n*[[Commerce Township, Michigan|Commerce Charter Township]]\n*[[Highland Township, Oakland County, Michigan|Highland Charter Township]]\n*[[Independence Township, Michigan|Independence Charter Township]]\n*[[Lyon Township, Oakland County, Michigan|Lyon Charter Township]]\n*[[Milford Township, Michigan|Milford Charter Township]]\n*[[Oakland Charter Township, Michigan|Oakland Charter Township]]\n*[[Orion Township, Michigan|Orion Charter Township]]\n*[[Oxford Charter Township, Michigan|Oxford Charter Township]]\n*[[Royal Oak Charter Township, Michigan|Royal Oak Charter Township]]\n*[[Springfield Township, Oakland County, Michigan|Springfield Charter Township]]\n*[[Waterford Township, Michigan|Waterford Charter Township]]\n*[[West Bloomfield Township, Michigan|West Bloomfield Charter Township]]\n*[[White Lake Township, Michigan|White Lake Charter Township]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Civil townships===\n*[[Addison Township, Michigan|Addison Township]]\n*[[Groveland Township, Michigan|Groveland Township]]\n*[[Holly Township, Michigan|Holly Township]]\n*[[Novi Township, Michigan|Novi Township]]\n*[[Rose Township, Oakland County, Michigan|Rose Township]]\n*[[Southfield Township, Michigan|Southfield Township]]\n\n===Unincorporated communities===\n{