{"title_page": "Jennie C. Jones", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jennie C. Jones\n| image         = Jennie C. Jones.jpg\n| birth_date   = 1968\n| birth_place   = [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]\n| alma mater    = {{ubl|[[School of the Art Institute of Chicago]]|[[Mason Gross School of the Arts]], [[Rutgers University]]}}\n| website       = http://www.jenniecjones.com/\n}}\n\n'''Jennie C. Jones''' (born 1968 in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]) is an African-American artist living and working in Brooklyn, New York. Her work has been described, by [[Ken Johnson (art critic)|Ken Johnson]], as evoking [[minimalism]], and paying tribute to the cross-pollination of different genres of music, especially [[jazz]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Ken|title=ART IN REVIEW Jennie C. Jones: 'Electric'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/30/arts/design/30galleries-003.html|accessdate=7 March 2015|agency=|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 30, 2010}}</ref> As an artist, she connects most of her work between art and sound. Such connections are made with multiple mediums, from paintings to sculptures and paper to audio collages.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Arning |first1=Bill |title=Jennie C. Jones: Compilation |url=https://www.artbook.com/9781941366080.html |website=artbook |publisher=Gregory R. Miller & Co. |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> In 2012, Jones was the recipient of the Joyce Alexander Wien Prize, one of the biggest awards given to an individual artist in the United States. The prize honors one African-American artist who has proven their commitment to innovation and creativity, with an award of 50,000 dollars.<ref name=\"Prize\">{{cite web|title=Studio Museum announces 2012 Joyce Alexander Wein Artist Prize awarded to Jennie C. Jones |url=http://artdaily.com/news/60301/Studio-Museum-announces-2012-Joyce-Alexander-Wein-Artist-Prize-awarded-to-Jennie-C--Jones#.VPtVL7DF8zs|website=artdaily.org|publisher=Art Daily|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\nIn December 2015 a 10-year survey of Jones's work, titled ''Compilation''<ref name=\"camh.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://camh.org/exhibitions/jennie-c-jones-compilation#.WLTGVRLyuRs|title=Jennie C. Jones: Compilation {{!}} Contemporary Arts Museum Houston|website=camh.org|access-date=2017-02-28}}</ref>'','' opened at the [[Contemporary Arts Museum Houston|Contemporary Arts Museum in Houston]], Texas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennie C. Jones Biography|url=http://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/index.php?v=artist&artist=5153403403728|website=|publisher=Sikkema Jenkins Co.|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nJennie C. Jones received her BFA at [[The School of the Art Institute of Chicago]], in 1991. She then graduated from Mason Gross School of the Arts at [[Rutgers University]], earning her MFA in 1996. In the summer of 1996, Jones was a participant at [[Skowhegan School of Painting and Sculpture]].<ref name=\"Prize\"/>\n\n==Work==\nJones is a visual and sonic artist whose paintings, sculptures, and works on paper incorporate ideas around minimalism, abstraction, Jazz, and Black history. [[Valerie Cassel Oliver]] noted in her \u201cOutside The Lines,\u201d catalogue essay, that \u201cworking in painting as well as sound, she has mined the politics, culture and aesthetic innovations of the mid-20th century and has emerged with sharp criticisms and astute queries that are now embedded in the work. Jones\u2019s work challenges us to understand the frameworks of modernism, which embraced black musical forms but excluded black visual art from its canon\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cassel Oliver|first1=Valerie|title=Outside the Lines|date=2014|publisher=Houston: Contemporary Arts Museum|location=Houston, Texas|page=145|isbn=9781933619460|oclc=902842760}}</ref> During ''Absorb / Diffuse,'' her fall 2011 exhibition at [[The Kitchen]] in New York City, Jones presented a piece titled ''From The Low'', which is a sound piece that has multiple music samples, ranging from jazz to modern electronica. ''From The Low'' presents her political statement: that African-American artists and musicians are absent from modernism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artspace.com/jennie_c__jones|title=Jennie C. Jones {{!}} Artspace|website=Artspace|access-date=2016-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amillionkeys.com/writing/jennie-c-jones-absorbdiffuse-at-the-kitchen/|title=Jennie C. Jones, Absorb/Diffuse\" The Wire, November 2011, pg. 81 {{!}} A Million Keys|website=A Million Keys|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> The samples used in this sound piece have been \"given a new context, perhaps to be classified in a category of black minimalism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bombmagazine.org/article/6274/jennie-c-jones|title=BOMB Magazine \u2014 Jennie C. Jones by Stephen Vitiello|website=bombmagazine.org|access-date=2016-03-09}}</ref>\n\nThe audio pieces are constructed using traditional sound editing methodologies and often have their origin in historic recordings. With the amalgamation of industrial acoustic materials, often used in recording studios and listening rooms, Jones's art focuses on building a bridge between two-dimensional works, architecture, and sound. Jennie has stated that \"conceptualism allows these different media to occupy the same space.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kennedy|first1=Randy|title=$50,000 Art Prize for Brooklyn Painter and Sculptor|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/01/21/50000-art-prize-for-brooklyn-painter-and-sculptor/|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Jones is a critic in the Sculpture Department at Yale University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://art.yale.edu/JennieJones|title=Yale University School of Art: Jennie Jones|website=art.yale.edu|access-date=2017-02-28}}</ref>\n\n<u>2000s- Early Work:</u>\n\nIn Jones's 'Selected Early Works,' she combined photography, visual arts, and audio art. Jones's website displays 30 images of her work completed in the 2000s. These works not only includes static, lasting art but also records of her installation art, such as her 2003 A/V Sound Work installation. These works, along with the works that follow, are easily accessible on her artist website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jenniecjones.com/|title=JENNIE C. JONES|website=JENNIE C. JONES|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>  Towards the end of the early years of Jones work she received the William H. Johnson Prize in 2008.  This is a $25,000 award given to African American artists based in the Los Angeles area.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=February 2009|title=Awards & Grants|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=aph&AN=36673457&site=ehost-live&scope=site|journal=Art in America|volume=97|issue=2|pages=152|via=}}</ref>\n\n<u>2009- Atlanta:</u>\n\nThis installation was a collection of visual works of acrylic painting, ink and collage works among other mediums. Jones's \"Atlanta\" exhibit at the Atlanta Contemporary Art Center.\n\n<u>2010- Electric:</u>\n\nThis collection is a variety of 2-D and 3-D works exhibited at Sikkema, Jenkins & Co. Gallery during July 8 - August 13, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/2010-exhibitions|title=2010 Exhibitions|website=www.sikkemajenkinsco.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\n<u>2011- Absorb, Silence:</u>\n\nThis installation at the Yerba Buena Center for the Arts in San Francisco, California was a combination of acrylic paintings, installation art, and various other 3-D art works.\n\n<u>2012- Harmonic Disruption:</u>\n\nThis exhibit was a collection of ink works on paper and installations of cable and speakers located in the Arratia Beer gallery in Berlin, Germany.\n\n<u>2013- Higher Resonance:</u>\n\nAt the Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Gallery in Washington, D.C., this exhibit contained works of acrylic paint, wood, fiberglass, mineral wool filling, and fabric.\n\n<u>2014- Tone:</u>\n\nIn a combination of acrylic paint on canvas and acoustic absorber panel, noise cancelling cable, and mixed media collage, Jones's ''Tone'' was displayed at Sikkema, Jenkins & Co. Gallery.\n\n<u>2015- Group:</u>\n\nThis exhibition was a group collection at the Sikkema, Jenkins & Co. Gallery. Jones, along with Josephine Halvorson and Leslie Hewitt displayed works of paintings and photography during 12/11/15 - 1/28/16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.galleriesnow.net/shows/jennie-c-jones-josephine-halvorson-leslie-hewitt/|title=Jennie C. Jones, Josephine Halvorson, Leslie Hewitt at Sikkema Jenkins & Co.|last=Jenkins|first=Sikkema|last2=Co|access-date=2019-03-02|last3=York|first3=New}}</ref>\n\n<u>2016- Compilation:</u>\n\nThis installation at The Contemporary Art Museum, Houston, TX, was on display from December 11, 2015 - March 27, 2016 and combined 2D art and 3D art.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://camh.org/event/jennie-c-jones-compilation/|title=Jennie C. Jones: Compilation|website=Contemporary Arts Museum Houston|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n<u>2017- Amplitude:</u>\n\nThis installation included both paint on canvas and acoustic soundboard. The Sikkema, Jenkins & Co. Gallery had this to say about Jones's Amplitude: \"Jennie C. Jones' work exposes the connections between conceptual and avant-garde African-American music and the cultural, political, and historical ideas surrounding Minimalism and Abstraction. Jones brings to light the unlikely alliances that emerged between the visual arts and the imprint of music, highlighting the way they became and continue to exist as tangible markers of social evolution and political strivings.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/amplitude|title=Amplitude September 8 - October 8, 2016|website=www.sikkemajenkinsco.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\n<u>2018- Alternative Takes:</u>\n\nThis installation was at the Patron Gallery, Chicago, IL from February 3 - March 18, 2018.  It combined acrylic paint and 3D art.\n\n<u>RPM (The Glass House):</u>\n\nThis installation brings together audio collages and works on paper.  It was displayed at The Glass House, New Cannon, CT from September 2018 - January 2019.\n\n==Exhibitions==\nJones's work has been exhibited all over the world.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gwinn|first1=Liz|title=Communications Manager|url=http://www.studiomuseum.org/sites/default/files/weinprize2012.pdf|website=www.studiomuseum.org|publisher=The Studio Museum|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> One of her first notable New York City group shows was [[Post-black art|\"Freestyle\"]] at the [[Studio Museum]] in Harlem, a show that included artists such as [[Sanford Biggers]], [[Mark Bradford]], [[Julie Mehretu]], and [[Rashid Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Thompson|first1=Donna|title=FREESTYLE: Review by Donna Thompson|date=2001|url=http://www.artwomen.org/currentissues1/freestyle/|website=artwomen.org|publisher=Art Women|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Selected solo exhibitions===\n*''Jennie C. Jones: RPM (revolutions per minute)'', [[Glass House|The Glass House]], New Canaan, Connecticut, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theglasshouse.org/whats-on/jennie-c-jones-rpmrevolutions-per-minute/|title=Jennie C. Jones: RPM(revolutions per minute) {{!}} The Glass House|website=theglasshouse.org|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n*''alternate takes'', PATRON, Chicago, IL, 2018\n*''Jennie C. Jones: Compilation,'' [[Contemporary Arts Museum Houston]], TX 2015-2016<ref name=\"camh.org\" />\n*''Tone'', Sikkema Jenkins Co., New York City, NY 2014<ref>{{cite web|last1=Briscoe|first1=Scott|title=Jennie C. Jones Exhibition Page|url=http://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/index.php?v=exhibition&exhibition=52dec7e9cd258|website=www.sikkemajenkins.com|publisher=Sikkema Jenkins Co.|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n*''Higher Resonance'', [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]], Washington, DC 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Higher Resonance Exhibition|url=http://www.hirshhorn.si.edu/collection/directions-jennie-c-jones/#collection=directions-jennie-c-jones&detail=http%3A//www.hirshhorn.si.edu/bio/directions-jennie-c-jones-higher-resonance/&title=Directions%3A+Jennie+C.+Jones%3A+Higher+Resonance|website=www.hirshhorn.si.edu|publisher=The Hirshhorn|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n*''Jennie C. Jones: Counterpoint'', Yerba Beuna Center for the Arts, San Francisco, CA 2011<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morales|first1=Julio C\u00e9sar|title=Interview with Jennie C. Jones|url=http://archive.ybca.org/jennie-c-jones|website=ybca.org|publisher=Yerba Buena Center for the Arts|access-date=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402112414/http://archive.ybca.org/jennie-c-jones#|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''Absorb/Diffuse'', [[The Kitchen]], New York City, NY, 2011<ref>{{cite web|last1=The Studio Museum in Harlem|title=Absorb/Diffuse \u2013 Jennie C. Jones at The Kitchen|url=http://www.studiomuseum.org/studio-blog/checkout/elsewhere/absorbdiffuse-jennie-c-jones-the-kitchen|website=www.studiomuseum.org|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n*''Song Containers & Objects'', Lawrimore Projects, Seattle, WA 2010<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennie C. Jones|url=http://www.lawrimoreproject.com/Artists/Pages/Jennie_C_Jones.html|website=www.lawrimoreproject.com|publisher=Lawrimore Project|access-date=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121200333/http://lawrimoreproject.com/Artists/Pages/Jennie_C_Jones.html#|archive-date=2014-11-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''Electric, Sikkema, Jenkins & Co.'', New York, NY 2010\n* ''The Walkman Compositions'',  Smack Mellon Gallery, New York City, NY 2009\n*''RED, BIRD, BLUE'', [[Atlanta Contemporary Art Center]], Atlanta, GA 2009\n*''Jones: Recomposing'', Arratia Beer Gallery, Berlin, Germany, 2007\n*''Simply Because You\u2019re Near Me'', [[Artists Space]], Project Room, New York, NY 2006\n*''Harlem/Haarlem'', Begane Grond Kunstcentrum, Utrecht, The Netherlands, 2000\n\n===Selected group exhibitions===\n*''Magnetic Fields: Expanding American Abstraction, 1960s to Today'', [[Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art]], Kansas City, MO; Travels to: [[National Museum of Women in the Arts]], Washington, DC, 2017\n*''Power'', [[Spr\u00fcth Magers|Spruth Magers]], Los Angeles, CA, 2017\n*''Gray Matters'', [[Wexner Center for the Arts]], Columbus, OH, 2017\n*''Black & Blue,'' [[Pulitzer Arts Foundation|The Pulitzer Foundation]], St. Louis, 2017\n*''Solidary and Solitary: The Pamela J. Joyner and Alfred J. Giuffrida Collection,'' [[Ogden Museum of Southern Art]], New Orleans, LA; Travels to: [[Nasher Museum of Art|Nasher Museum of Art at Duke University]], Durham, NC; [[Snite Museum of Art]] at the University of Norte Dame, Notre Dame, IN; The [[Smart Museum of Art]] at the University of Chicago, Chicago, IL; [[Baltimore Museum of Art]], Baltimore, MD; [[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive|Berkeley Art Museum]], Berkeley, CA; [[P\u00e9rez Art Museum Miami|Perez Art Museum Miami]], Miami, FL, 2017\n*''Artists of Color,'' The Underground Museum, Los Angeles, CA, 2017\n*''Cells'', Marianne Boesky Gallery, New York, NY, 2017\n*''Cut-Up'', Franklin Street Works, Stamford, CT, 2016\n*''From Minimalism into Algorithm,'' The Kitchen, New York, NY, 2016\n*''James Baldwin/Jim Brown and the Children,'' The Artist\u2019s Institute, New York, NY, 2016\n*''Variations: Conversations in and Around Abstract Painting'', [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], Los Angeles, CA 2014-2015\n*''Outside the Lines: Black in the Abstract, Part 2'', [[Contemporary Arts Museum Houston]], Houston, TX 2014\n*''Roughneck Constructivists'' Curated by [[Kara Walker]] at the ICA in Philadelphia, PA 2014\n*''SILENCE'' a survey exhibition curated by Toby Kamps, [[The Menil Collection]], Houston, TX 2012\n*''With Hidden Noise'' a group Exhibition Curated by [[Stephen Vitiello]], [[Aspen Art Museum]], Aspen, CO 2011\n*''30 Seconds off an Inch'', [[The Studio Museum in Harlem]], New York, NY 2010\n*''This-Has-Been,'' On Stellar Rays, Gallery 133, New York, NY 2009\n*''(Dis)Concert'', Steve Turner Contemporary, Los Angeles, CA 2008\n*''Black Light, White Noise: Sound & Light in Contemporary Art'', [[Contemporary Arts Museum Houston]], Houston, TX 2007\n*''Pa*per*ing'', Deutsch Bank, New York City, NY 2006\n*''Double Consciousness: Black Conceptual Art Since 1970'', Houston Contemporary Art Museum, Houston, TX 2005\n*''Freestyle'', [[Santa Monica Museum of Art]], Santa Monica, CA 2001\n*''Freestyle'', The Studio Museum of Harlem, New York City, NY 2001\n*''Current/Undercurrent'', [[Brooklyn Museum]], 1997<ref name=BioPDF>{{cite web|title=Jennie C. Jones \u2013 Exhibitions |url=http://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/files/pdfs/8319_JennieCJones_CV_2013.pdf|website=www.sikkemajenkins.com|publisher=Sikkema Jenkins Gallery|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Fellowships and residencies==\n*Rauschenberg Residency, Captiva FL 2014\n*The Lower East Side Printshop \u2013 Special Editions Resident, 2011\n*Rockefeller Foundation Bellagio Study Center \u2013 Italy, March 2008\n*American Academy in Rome, Italy, Visiting Artist - April 2008\n*Liguria Study Center for the Arts & Humanities Fellow \u2013 Genova, Italy, 2004\n*[[Cit\u00e9 internationale des arts]] in Paris, 2002\u201303\n*Lower Manhattan Cultural Council Residency World Trade Center, 1999<ref name=BioPDF />\n*Skowhegan School of Painting and Sculpture (1996)<ref name=\"SikkemaJenkins\">{{cite web|title=SikkemaJenkins&Co:Artists:Jennie C. Jones|url=http://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/index.php?v=artist&artist=5153403403728|publisher=Sikkema Jenkins & Co|accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*Robert Rauschenberg Award, Foundation for Contemporary Arts, 2016<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.foundationforcontemporaryarts.org/recipients/jennie-c-jones|title=Jennie C. Jones :: Foundation for Contemporary Arts|website=www.foundationforcontemporaryarts.org|access-date=2017-02-28}}</ref>\n*Joan Mitchell Award Grantee, 2013\n*The Joyce Alexander Wein Prize, 2012\n*Art Matters Grant, 2012<ref>{{cite web|title=Grantee List|url=http://www.artmattersfoundation.org/grantees/year/two-thousand-seven-to-present|publisher=Art Matters Foundation|access-date=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150306012649/http://www.artmattersfoundation.org/grantees/year/two-thousand-seven-to-present#|archive-date=2015-03-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*William H. Johnson Prize, 2008\n*Creative Capital Grantee, 2008\n*Pollock-Krasner Grant Recipient, 2000<ref name=BioPDF />\n\n==Collections==\n*BNY Mellon, Pittsburgh, PA\n*Deutsche Bank, New York, NY\n*[[Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum]], New York, NY\n*Mott-Warsh Collection, Flint, MI\n*The Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden, [[Smithsonian Institution]], Washington, DC\n*The Zimmerli Museum, Rutgers University, New Jersey\n*[[Studio Museum in Harlem|The Studio Museum in Harlem]], New York City, NY\n*[[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] (LACMA), Los Angeles, CA\n*The Americas Collection, Deutsche Bank\n*Weil, Gotshal & Manges, New York City, NY<ref name=BioPDF />\n*[[Museum of Modern Art]], New York, NY\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.artinamericamagazine.com/reviews/jennie-c-jones/print/ Art in America Review for ''Absorb/Diffuse'' at The Kitchen 2011]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/30/arts/design/30galleries-003.html Ken Johnson's review of ''Electric'' at Sikkema Jenkins and Company 2010]\n*[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9B05EEDD153EF933A25751C0A9609C8B63 Holland Cotter's review of ''Simply Because You're Near Me'' at Artists Space 2006]\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2001/05/11/arts/art-review-a-full-studio-museum-show-starts-with-28-young-artists-and-a-shoehorn.html Holland Cotter's review of Freestyle at the Studio Museum in Harlem 2001]\n*[http://arts.gov/art-works/2013/art-works-podcast-jennie-c-jones National Endowment for the Arts Interview Podcast]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20150228132114/http://soundcheck.wnyc.org/story/266104-jennie-c-jones-jazz-and-art/ ''Jennie C. Jones: On Jazz and Art interview on Sound Check with John Schaefer 2013]\n*[https://soundcloud.com/jcjones-1/harmonic-distortion Listen to ''Harmonic Distortion'']\n*[https://soundcloud.com/jcjones-1/cassette-mixing-elvin-jones Listen to ''Cassette Mixing with Elvin and Flute'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Jennie C.}}\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women artists]]\n[[Category:African-American contemporary artists]]\n[[Category:Artists from Cincinnati]]\n[[Category:Mason Gross School of the Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:School of the Art Institute of Chicago alumni]]\n[[Category:Skowhegan School of Painting and Sculpture alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jennie C. Jones\n| image         = Jennie C. Jones.jpg\n| birth_date   = 1968\n| birth_place   = [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]\n| alma mater    = {{ubl|[[School of the Art Institute of Chicago]]|[[Mason Gross School of the Arts]], [[Rutgers University]]}}\n| website       = http://www.jenniecjones.com/\n}}\n\n'''Jennie C. Jones''' (born 1968 in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]]) is an African-American artist living and working in Brooklyn, New York. Her work has been described, by [[Ken Johnson (art critic)|Ken Johnson]], as evoking [[minimalism]], and paying tribute to the cross-pollination of different genres of music, especially [[jazz]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Ken|title=ART IN REVIEW Jennie C. Jones: 'Electric'|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/30/arts/design/30galleries-003.html|accessdate=7 March 2015|agency=|newspaper=The New York Times|date=July 30, 2010}}</ref> As an artist, she connects most of her work between art and sound. Such connections are made with multiple mediums, from paintings to sculptures and paper to audio collages.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Arning |first1=Bill |title=Jennie C. Jones: Compilation |url=https://www.artbook.com/9781941366080.html |website=artbook |publisher=Gregory R. Miller & Co. |accessdate=10 March 2020}}</ref> In 2012, Jones was the recipient of the Joyce Alexander Wien Prize, one of the biggest awards given to an individual artist in the United States. The prize honors one African-American artist who has proven their commitment to innovation and creativity, with an award of 50,000 dollars.<ref name=\"Prize\">{{cite web|title=Studio Museum announces 2012 Joyce Alexander Wein Artist Prize awarded to Jennie C. Jones |url=http://artdaily.com/news/60301/Studio-Museum-announces-2012-Joyce-Alexander-Wein-Artist-Prize-awarded-to-Jennie-C--Jones#.VPtVL7DF8zs|website=artdaily.org|publisher=Art Daily|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\nIn December 2015 a 10-year survey of Jones's work, titled ''Compilation''<ref name=\"camh.org\">{{Cite web|url=http://camh.org/exhibitions/jennie-c-jones-compilation#.WLTGVRLyuRs|title=Jennie C. Jones: Compilation {{!}} Contemporary Arts Museum Houston|website=camh.org|access-date=2017-02-28}}</ref>'','' opened at the [[Contemporary Arts Museum Houston|Contemporary Arts Museum in Houston]], Texas.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennie C. Jones Biography|url=http://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/index.php?v=artist&artist=5153403403728|website=|publisher=Sikkema Jenkins Co.|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nJennie C. Jones received her BFA at [[The School of the Art Institute of Chicago]], in 1991. She then graduated from Mason Gross School of the Arts at [[Rutgers University]], earning her MFA in 1996. In the summer of 1996, Jones was a participant at [[Skowhegan School of Painting and Sculpture]].<ref name=\"Prize\"/>\n\n==Work==\nJones is a visual and sonic artist whose paintings, sculptures, and works on paper incorporate ideas around minimalism, abstraction, Jazz, and Black history. [[Valerie Cassel Oliver]] noted in her \u201cOutside The Lines,\u201d catalogue essay, that \u201cworking in painting as well as sound, she has mined the politics, culture and aesthetic innovations of the mid-20th century and has emerged with sharp criticisms and astute queries that are now embedded in the work. Jones\u2019s work challenges us to understand the frameworks of modernism, which embraced black musical forms but excluded black visual art from its canon\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Cassel Oliver|first1=Valerie|title=Outside the Lines|date=2014|publisher=Houston: Contemporary Arts Museum|location=Houston, Texas|page=145|isbn=9781933619460|oclc=902842760}}</ref> During ''Absorb / Diffuse,'' her fall 2011 exhibition at [[The Kitchen]] in New York City, Jones presented a piece titled ''From The Low'', which is a sound piece that has multiple music samples, ranging from jazz to modern electronica. ''From The Low'' presents her political statement: that African-American artists and musicians are absent from modernism.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.artspace.com/jennie_c__jones|title=Jennie C. Jones {{!}} Artspace|website=Artspace|access-date=2016-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://amillionkeys.com/writing/jennie-c-jones-absorbdiffuse-at-the-kitchen/|title=Jennie C. Jones, Absorb/Diffuse\" The Wire, November 2011, pg. 81 {{!}} A Million Keys|website=A Million Keys|access-date=2019-03-22}}</ref> The samples used in this sound piece have been \"given a new context, perhaps to be classified in a category of black minimalism\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bombmagazine.org/article/6274/jennie-c-jones|title=BOMB Magazine \u2014 Jennie C. Jones by Stephen Vitiello|website=bombmagazine.org|access-date=2016-03-09}}</ref>\n\nThe audio pieces are constructed using traditional sound editing methodologies and often have their origin in historic recordings. With the amalgamation of industrial acoustic materials, often used in recording studios and listening rooms, Jones's art focuses on building a bridge between two-dimensional works, architecture, and sound. Jennie has stated that \"conceptualism allows these different media to occupy the same space.\u201d<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kennedy|first1=Randy|title=$50,000 Art Prize for Brooklyn Painter and Sculptor|url=http://artsbeat.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/01/21/50000-art-prize-for-brooklyn-painter-and-sculptor/|newspaper=The New York Times|accessdate=7 March 2015}}</ref> Jones is a critic in the Sculpture Department at Yale University.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://art.yale.edu/JennieJones|title=Yale University School of Art: Jennie Jones|website=art.yale.edu|access-date=2017-02-28}}</ref>\n\n<u>2000's- Early Work:</u>\n\nIn Jones's 'Selected Early Works,' she combined photography, visual arts, and audio art. Jones's website displays 30 images of her work completed in the 2000's. These works not only includes static, lasting art but also records of her installation art, such as her 2003 A/V Sound Work installation. These works, along with the works that follow, are easily accessible on her artist website.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jenniecjones.com/|title=JENNIE C. JONES|website=JENNIE C. JONES|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>  Towards the end of the early years of Jones work she received the William H. Johnson Prize in 2008.  This is a $25,000 award given to African American artists based in the Los Angeles area.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=|first=|date=February 2009|title=Awards & Grants|url=http://search.ebscohost.com/login.aspx?direct=true&db=aph&AN=36673457&site=ehost-live&scope=site|journal=Art in America|volume=97|issue=2|pages=152|via=}}</ref>\n\n<u>2009- Atlanta:</u>\n\nThis installation was a collection of visual works of acrylic painting, ink and collage works among other mediums. Jones's \"Atlanta\" exhibit at the Atlanta Contemporary Art Center.\n\n<u>2010- Electric:</u>\n\nThis collection is a variety of 2-D and 3-D works exhibited at Sikkema, Jenkins & Co. Gallery during July 8 - August 13, 2010.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/2010-exhibitions|title=2010 Exhibitions|website=www.sikkemajenkinsco.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\n<u>2011- Absorb, Silence:</u>\n\nThis installation at the Yerba Buena Center for the Arts in San Francisco, California was a combination of acrylic paintings, installation art, and various other 3-D art works.\n\n<u>2012- Harmonic Disruption:</u>\n\nThis exhibit was a collection of ink works on paper and installations of cable and speakers located in the Arratia Beer gallery in Berlin, Germany.\n\n<u>2013- Higher Resonance:</u>\n\nAt the Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Gallery in Washington, D.C., this exhibit contained works of acrylic paint, wood, fiberglass, mineral wool filling, and fabric.\n\n<u>2014- Tone:</u>\n\nIn a combination of acrylic paint on canvas and acoustic absorber panel, noise cancelling cable, and mixed media collage, Jones's ''Tone'' was displayed at Sikkema, Jenkins & Co. Gallery.\n\n<u>2015- Group:</u>\n\nThis exhibition was a group collection at the Sikkema, Jenkins & Co. Gallery. Jones, along with Josephine Halvorson and Leslie Hewitt displayed works of paintings and photography during 12/11/15 - 1/28/16.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.galleriesnow.net/shows/jennie-c-jones-josephine-halvorson-leslie-hewitt/|title=Jennie C. Jones, Josephine Halvorson, Leslie Hewitt at Sikkema Jenkins & Co.|last=Jenkins|first=Sikkema|last2=Co|access-date=2019-03-02|last3=York|first3=New}}</ref>\n\n<u>2016- Compilation:</u>\n\nThis installation at The Contemporary Art Museum, Houston, TX, was on display from December 11, 2015 - March 27, 2016 and combined 2D art and 3D art.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://camh.org/event/jennie-c-jones-compilation/|title=Jennie C. Jones: Compilation|website=Contemporary Arts Museum Houston|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-25}}</ref>\n\n<u>2017- Amplitude:</u>\n\nThis installation included both paint on canvas and acoustic soundboard. The Sikkema, Jenkins & Co. Gallery had this to say about Jones's Amplitude: \"Jennie C. Jones' work exposes the connections between conceptual and avant-garde African-American music and the cultural, political, and historical ideas surrounding Minimalism and Abstraction. Jones brings to light the unlikely alliances that emerged between the visual arts and the imprint of music, highlighting the way they became and continue to exist as tangible markers of social evolution and political strivings.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/amplitude|title=Amplitude September 8 - October 8, 2016|website=www.sikkemajenkinsco.com|access-date=2019-03-02}}</ref>\n\n<u>2018- Alternative Takes:</u>\n\nThis installation was at the Patron Gallery, Chicago, IL from February 3 - March 18, 2018.  It combined acrylic paint and 3D art.\n\n<u>RPM (The Glass House):</u>\n\nThis installation brings together audio collages and works on paper.  It was displayed at The Glass House, New Cannon, CT from September 2018 - January 2019.\n\n==Exhibitions==\nJones's work has been exhibited all over the world.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Gwinn|first1=Liz|title=Communications Manager|url=http://www.studiomuseum.org/sites/default/files/weinprize2012.pdf|website=www.studiomuseum.org|publisher=The Studio Museum|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref> One of her first notable New York City group shows was [[Post-black art|\"Freestyle\"]] at the [[Studio Museum]] in Harlem, a show that included artists such as [[Sanford Biggers]], [[Mark Bradford]], [[Julie Mehretu]], and [[Rashid Johnson]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Thompson|first1=Donna|title=FREESTYLE: Review by Donna Thompson|date=2001|url=http://www.artwomen.org/currentissues1/freestyle/|website=artwomen.org|publisher=Art Women|accessdate=22 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Selected solo exhibitions===\n*''Jennie C. Jones: RPM (revolutions per minute)'', [[Glass House|The Glass House]], New Canaan, Connecticut, 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theglasshouse.org/whats-on/jennie-c-jones-rpmrevolutions-per-minute/|title=Jennie C. Jones: RPM(revolutions per minute) {{!}} The Glass House|website=theglasshouse.org|access-date=2019-05-06}}</ref>\n*''alternate takes'', PATRON, Chicago, IL, 2018\n*''Jennie C. Jones: Compilation,'' [[Contemporary Arts Museum Houston]], TX 2015-2016<ref name=\"camh.org\" />\n*''Tone'', Sikkema Jenkins Co., New York City, NY 2014<ref>{{cite web|last1=Briscoe|first1=Scott|title=Jennie C. Jones Exhibition Page|url=http://www.sikkemajenkinsco.com/index.php?v=exhibition&exhibition=52dec7e9cd258|website=www.sikkemajenkins.com|publisher=Sikkema Jenkins Co.|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n*''Higher Resonance'', [[Hirshhorn Museum and Sculpture Garden]], Washington, DC 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Higher Resonance Exhibition|url=http://www.hirshhorn.si.edu/collection/directions-jennie-c-jones/#collection=directions-jennie-c-jones&detail=http%3A//www.hirshhorn.si.edu/bio/directions-jennie-c-jones-higher-resonance/&title=Directions%3A+Jennie+C.+Jones%3A+Higher+Resonance|website=www.hirshhorn.si.edu|publisher=The Hirshhorn|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n*''Jennie C. Jones: Counterpoint'', Yerba Beuna Center for the Arts, San Francisco, CA 2011<ref>{{cite web|last1=Morales|first1=Julio C\u00e9sar|title=Interview with Jennie C. Jones|url=http://archive.ybca.org/jennie-c-jones|website=ybca.org|publisher=Yerba Buena Center for the Arts|access-date=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402112414/http://archive.ybca.org/jennie-c-jones#|archive-date=2015-04-02|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''Absorb/Diffuse'', [[The Kitchen]], New York City, NY, 2011<ref>{{cite web|last1=The Studio Museum in Harlem|title=Absorb/Diffuse \u2013 Jennie C. Jones at The Kitchen|url=http://www.studiomuseum.org/studio-blog/checkout/elsewhere/absorbdiffuse-jennie-c-jones-the-kitchen|website=www.studiomuseum.org|accessdate=23 February 2015}}</ref>\n*''Song Containers & Objects'', Lawrimore Projects, Seattle, WA 2010<ref>{{cite web|title=Jennie C. Jones|url=http://www.lawrimoreproject.com/Artists/Pages/Jennie_C_Jones.html|website=www.lawrimoreproject.com|publisher=Lawrimore Project|access-date=23 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141121200333/http://lawrimoreproject.com/Artists/Pages/Jennie_C_Jones.html#|archive-date=2014-11-21|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n*''Electric, Sikkema, Jenkins & Co.'', New York, NY 2010\n* ''The Walkman Compositions'',  Smack Mellon Gallery, New York City, NY 2009\n*''RED, BIRD, BLUE'', [[Atlanta Contemporary Art Center]], Atlanta, GA 2009\n*''Jones: Recomposing'', Arratia Beer Gallery, Berlin, Germany, 2007\n*''Simply Because You\u2019re Near Me'', [[Artists Space]], Project Room, New York, NY 2006\n*''Harlem/Haarlem'', Begane Grond Kunstcentrum, Utrecht, The Netherlands, 2000\n\n===Selected group exhibitions===\n*''Magnetic Fields: Expanding American Abstraction, 1960s to Today'', [[Kemper Museum of Contemporary Art]], Kansas City, MO; Travels to: [[National Museum of Women in the Arts]], Washington, DC, 2017\n*''Power'', [[Spr\u00fcth Magers|Spruth Magers]], Los Angeles, CA, 2017\n*''Gray Matters'', [[Wexner Center for the Arts]], Columbus, OH, 2017\n*''Black & Blue,'' [[Pulitzer Arts Foundation|The Pulitzer Foundation]], St. Louis, 2017\n*''Solidary and Solitary: The Pamela J. Joyner and Alfred J. Giuffrida Collection,'' [[Ogden Museum of Southern Art]], New Orleans, LA; Travels to: [[Nasher Museum of Art|Nasher Museum of Art at Duke University]], Durham, NC; [[Snite Museum of Art]] at the University of Norte Dame, Notre Dame, IN; The [[Smart Museum of Art]] at the University of Chicago, Chicago, IL; [[Baltimore Museum of Art]], Baltimore, MD; [[Berkeley Art Museum and Pacific Film Archive|Berkeley Art Museum]], Berkeley, CA; [[P\u00e9rez Art Museum Miami|Perez Art Museum Miami]], Miami, FL, 2017\n*''Artists of Color,'' The Underground Museum, Los Angeles, CA, 2017\n*''Cells'', Marianne Boesky Gallery, New York, NY, 2017\n*''Cut-Up'', Franklin Street Works, Stamford, CT, 2016\n*''From Minimalism into Algorithm,'' The Kitchen, New York, NY, 2016\n*''James Baldwin/Jim Brown and the Children,'' The Artist\u2019s Institute, New York, NY, 2016\n*''Variations: Conversations in and Around Abstract Painting'', [[Los Angeles County Muse